rt of a camera (foreground) and the antenna of an unmanned Agena target vehicle—used during the Gemini program for rendezvous and docking practice—are visible in the left corner of the frame.%0a%3c %0a%3c Released in January, the picture is among thousands of high-resolution digital scans that are being created as part of the [[http://tothemoon.ser.asu.edu/gallery/gemini | Project Gemini Online Digital Archive]].%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/01/pictures/120123-nasa-space-missions-project-gemini-moon-digital-science/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It '''%0a%3c %0a%3c ''''''%0a%3c %0a%3c "Many pictures of suited astronauts don't show their faces. I like the sense of humanity in this picture, even though most of his face is in shadow."—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Cloud Curls%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:nasa-rocket-launch-strange-clouds-white_50493_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Photograph courtesy Chris Perry, NASA%0a%3c %0a%3c Loops of wispy [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/earth/earths-atmosphere/clouds-article/ | clouds]] rise like smoke rings against a background of stars in March—the products of a [[http://www.nasa.gov/ | NASA]] rocket launch designed to study the upper-level jet stream. (See [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/photos/clouds/ | more cloud pictures]].)%0a%3c %0a%3c The space agency launched five consecutive sounding rockets from its [[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/wallops/home/index.html | Wallops Flight Facility]] in Virginia as part of the [[http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/sunearth/missions/atrex.html | Anomalous Transport Rocket Experiment, or ATREX.]] Once aloft, each suborbital rocket released a chemical tracer at altitudes between 50 and 90 miles (80 and 145 kilometers)—near the edge of space.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/03/pictures/120327-nasa-rockets-clouds-wallops-jet-stream-edge-space-science/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c ''''''%0a%3c %0a%3c "A photojournalism teacher once pointed out to me that the best photos of an event can come before it's supposed to start or well after it's ended. This is a perfect example!"—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! "Smiley" Eclipse%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:solar-eclipse-2012-annular-ring-of-fire-philippines_53563_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Photograph by Bullit Marquez, AP%0a%3c %0a%3c A [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/space/solar-system/solar-eclipse-article/ | solar eclipse]] turns the disk of the sun into a wide orange grin over Gumaca in the [[http://travel.nationalgeographic.com/travel/countries/philippines-guide/ | Philippines]] in May.%0a%3c %0a%3c Although the sun is only minimally covered in this picture, the so-called annular eclipse went on to create a "ring of fire" for sky-watchers in parts of Asia and the U.S. West. (See more[[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/01/photogalleries/100115-eclipse-ring-fire-annular-pictures/ |  annular solar eclipse pictures]].)%0a%3c %0a%3c An annular eclipse happens when the moon lines up between Earth and the sun and when the dark moon's apparent diameter is smaller than the visible disk of the sun, leaving a ring—or annulus—of fiery light around the edges.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/05/pictures/120521-solar-eclipse-2012-pictures-annular-science/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c ''''''%0a%3c %0a%3c "While an astronomer might have been disappointed by these clouds, I felt that they gave this photograph an interesting, brooding feeling. It evokes the same sense of mystery that Earthlings must have felt for thousands of years as the sun grew slowly dark during an eclipse. A more synthetic or 'clean' image of an eclipse doesn't feel as powerful to me as a view like this."—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Helix Nebula%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space179-helix-cats-eye-nebula_47258_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy ESO%0a%3c %0a%3c '''''''''The intricate structure of the Helix Nebula, seen in January, is featured as one of National Geographic News editor's picks for the best space pictures of 2012. ([[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/photos/nebulae-gallery/ | See more nebula pictures]].)'''%0a%3c %0a%3c The rust-colored remains of a star like our sun, the Helix puffed up as it died and shed its shells of gas and dust into space.%0a%3c %0a%3c In visible light, fine details in the Helix are largely obscured by dust. But the infrared view—snapped by the [[http://www.eso.org/public/ | European Southern Observatory']]s VISTA telescope—can pierce this veil to see radiating filaments of cooler gas in the rings as well as a faint halo of thinly spread gas that extends to at least four light-years from the dead star's core.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/01/pictures/120120-best-space-pictures-179-costa-concordia/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "This deep-space picture has an unusual sense of scale: The individual bright spots placed throughout the image give it a 3-D feeling of depth, while the fine detail hints at the huge size of this planetary nebula."—''''''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Blooming Seas%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space179-phytoplankton-bloom_47270_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy ESA%0a%3c %0a%3c A phytoplankton bloom traces a figure eight in the South Atlantic Ocean, about 373 miles (600 kilometers) east of the British-held Falkland Islands in a [[http://www.esa.int/export/esaCP/index.html | European Space Agency]] satellite picture from January.%0a%3c %0a%3c Phytoplankton are microscopic organisms that make up the base of the marine food chain. In spring and summer, upwelling nutrients from deeper waters can fuel massive plankton blooms at the surface.%0a%3c %0a%3c Different types and quantities of phytoplankton appear as differently colored blooms, as seen in the varying shades of blue and green above.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/01/pictures/120120-best-space-pictures-179-costa-concordia/#/space179-phytoplankton-bloom_47270_600x450.jpg | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "I like the way that this satellite image has a sense of movement to it; most look so static."—''Chris Combs, news photo editor ''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Crater Fan%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space180-mars-crater_47844_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy U. Arizona/NASA%0a%3c %0a%3c A fan-shaped deposit decorates the floor of a Martian impact crater in a [[http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/MRO/main/index.html | NASA Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]] picture released in January.%0a%3c %0a%3c The ancient fan looks similar to modern deltas on Earth, which form when water in a channel flows into a larger body of water, as with the Nile Delta in Egypt. As the water spreads out, it moves slower and drops any sediment it's carrying, creating the fanlike structure.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/01/pictures/120127-best-space-pictures-180-sun-plasma-blue-marble-mars/#/space180-mars-crater_47844_600x450.jpg | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "I could look at the rich detail of this image all day."''—''''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Star Cradle%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space182-carina-nebula_48557_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy ESO%0a%3c %0a%3c A February picture from the [[http://www.eso.org/public/ | European Southern Observatory]]'s Very Large Telescope is the most detailed infrared view yet of the Carina Nebula. This bustling stellar nursery sits about 7,500 light-years from Earth and is home to several of the brightest and most massive stars known.%0a%3c %0a%3c Radiation from the hot, young stars inside causes the large nebula to glow brightly in visible light. But the new infrared view can also pierce the space cloud's veil of dust to see hundreds of thousands of fainter stars that were previously invisible.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/02/pictures/120210-best-space-pictures-mars-moon-sun-stars-182-science/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "I once watched an artist in Times Square use canned spray paint and a deft hand to make the most fantastic planets and nebulae in a night sky. This image of a real nebula is even more dramatic than his painting!"''—''''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Southern Sky Show%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space188-soyuz-orbit-northern-lights-earth-space_50367_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Photograph courtesy NASA%0a%3c %0a%3c From their vantage point high above Earth in March, astronauts on the [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/space/space-exploration/international-space-station-article/ | International Space Station]] were able to capture daybreak (left) and nighttime auroras in a single frame.%0a%3c %0a%3c Snapped over the Indian Ocean, the picture also shows a Russian Soyuz spacecraft (center) and a Progress resupply ship docked at the station.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/03/pictures/120322-best-space-pictures-188-auroras-mars-robot/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c ''''''%0a%3c %0a%3c "I like the way that this photograph gives a sense of what it must be like to look o