 polar region, which are lined and speckled by defrosting winter ice.%0a%3c %0a%3c White regions indicate where fine-grained frost still rims the polar dunes. Dark blotches, meanwhile, are most likely made from sediment kicked up by carbon dioxide "geysers" created as ice layers sublimate, or turn directly from a solid to a gas.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/04/pictures/120426-best-space-pictures-193-sun-auroras-sombrero#/space193-north-polar-dunes-mars_52135_600x450.jpg | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c ''''''%0a%3c %0a%3c "The grittiness of this image reminded me of dirty, melting snow here on Earth. I try to find space images that bring it home, showing us something familiar that we can relate to."—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Thor's Helmet%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space194-thors-helmet_52556_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy SSRO/PROMPT/CTIO%0a%3c %0a%3c Before he joins [[http://marvel.com/avengers_movie/ | the Avengers]], Thor may need to retrieve his helmet—which is floating in space 15,000 light-years away.%0a%3c %0a%3c Also known as NGC 2359, Thor's Helmet is a nebula found in the constellation Canis Major. As seen in this picture from May—taken by the [[http://www.ctio.noao.edu/noao/ | Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory]] in Chile—the cosmic cloud of dust and gas is being shaped like a winged helm by outpourings of radiation from the massive stars inside.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/05/pictures/120504-best-space-pictures-194-thor-avengers-moon-r2-nebula/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "This is a beautiful picture, with a rewarding complexity; as you keep looking, more and more detail turns up. Astro-imagers, take note of the [[http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im1106.html | careful colorization]] that went into this multispectrum image."—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Arctic Aurora%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space201-aurora-mountains_55457_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Photograph by Max Edin, Your Shot%0a%3c %0a%3c Earth's most famous light formation hangs over a landscape saturated by the glow of a full moon in Longyearbyen, [[http://travel.nationalgeographic.com/travel/countries/norway-guide/ | Norway]], in June.%0a%3c %0a%3c The photographer, who recently submitted this image to National Geographic's Your Shot, said it was the most beautiful northern lights display he had ever witnessed. Referred to as the [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/space/universe/auroras-heavenly-lights/ | aurora borealis]] around the Arctic Circle, the light show also appears in southern polar latitudes, where it's known as the aurora australis.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/06/pictures/120625-best-space-pictures-201-china-aurora-spy-plane/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "We have the good fortune of being able to run many beautiful aurora photographs each year. I like the delicate color of the moonlit mountains in this one and the simplicity of the aurora itself."''—''''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Farewell Voyage%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space214-shuttle-over-houston_59481_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Photograph by Sheri Locke, NASA%0a%3c %0a%3c The last of five shuttles in the U.S. space shuttle program,[[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/kennedy/shuttleoperations/orbiters/endeavour-info.html | Endeavour]] was formally retired in September and made its final aerial journey, bound for the [[http://www.californiasciencecenter.org/ | California Science Museum (CSC)]] in downtown Los Angeles.%0a%3c %0a%3c Endeavour was the youngest of the shuttle fleet, having been built after 