toms in the ionosphere above the planet's magnetic North and South Poles. The energy released by these collisions creates glowing colors some 60 to 620 miles (97 to 1,000 kilometers) aloft.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/11/pictures/121112-best-space-pictures-mars-auroras-nebula-stars-221/ | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It '''%0a%3c %0a%3c "This is a beautifully simple star-trail photograph. I like the vivid colors on the horizon and the understated foreground. Although it's a good rule of thumb to incorporate a prominent foreground into a night-sky picture like this, sometimes it's best to let the stars do the talking!"—''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Ringed Beauty%0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:space224-saturn-rings_61802_600x450.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c Image courtesy Caltech/SSI/NASA%0a%3c %0a%3c A steeply inclined orbit gives [[http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/cassini/main/index.html | NASA's Cassini spacecraft]] a spectacular view of [[http://science.nationalgeographic.com/science/space/solar-system/saturn-article/ | Saturn]]'s rings, composed of ice and rock.%0a%3c %0a%3c Released in November, this image was taken at a distance of about 1.5 million miles (2.4 million kilometers) on August 19, 2012, with a wide-angle camera.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/11/pictures/121130-best-space-pictures-224-saturn-storm/#/space224-saturn-rings_61802_600x450.jpg | Full story&gt;&gt;]]%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Why We Love It'''%0a%3c %0a%3c "The deep shadows and high contrast of this elegant picture remind me of a silver gelatin black-and-white photograph. I cropped a [[http://photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov/catalog/PIA14636 | tiny moon]] off of the very top of this image to keep it simple, and because it wasn't very easy to see once the picture was sized down."''—''''Chris Combs, news photo editor''%0a%3c %0a%3c Published December 11, 2012%